, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oakington, Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1520–1582":"1520–1582","1554–1616":"1554–1616","1561–Female":"1561–Deceased","1565–1600":"1565–1600","1566–Male":"1566–Deceased","1568–Female":"1568–Deceased","1570–Male":"1570–Deceased","1572–1617":"1572–1617","–Female":"Deceased","16 November 1561":"16 November 1561","1572":"1572","1561":"1561","1582":"1582","1570":"1570","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1600":"1600","1566":"1566","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","12 November 1554":"12 November 1554","1585":"1585","about 1568":"about 1568","about 1572":"about 1572","1617":"1617","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leete","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Leet  .","History: An early American bearer of this name was one of the founders ofGuilford, CT. William Leete (<i>c.</i> 1613–83), a colonial governorof New Haven colony and CT, was born at Dodington, Huntingtonshire,England. He converted to Puritanism and sailed for America to escapepersecution in May 1639."],"variants":[{"name":"Leet","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a watercourse orroad junction, Old English <i>gelǣt</i>, or a habitational namefrom Leat in Devon, or The Leete in Essex, named with this element."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":28,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":37,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":48,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":64,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":66,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":99,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas Leete was born in England. She had at least 3 sons and 4 daughters with Thomas Leete II."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1520–1582":"1520–1582","1554–1616":"1554–1616","1561–Female":"1561–Surnud","1565–1600":"1565–1600","1566–Male":"1566–Surnud","1568–Female":"1568–Surnud","1570–Male":"1570–Surnud","1572–1617":"1572–1617","–Female":"Surnud","16 November 1561":"16. november 1561","1572":"1572","1561":"1561","1582":"1582","1570":"1570","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1600":"1600","1566":"1566","1565":"1565","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","12 November 1554":"12. november 1554","1585":"1585","about 1568":"umbes 1568","about 1572":"umbes 1572","1617":"1617","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Oakington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oakington, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Oakington